                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                <placeName>Richmond</placeName>\n                <date>19 July/36</date>\n            </p>\n            <p>\n                <addressee>Revd. Mr Leeser</addressee>\n            </p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">My dear friend</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(3)\">Some months past I was called upon<lb/> by the <persName>Revd. Mr\n                        A<add>?</add></persName> who asked me if the 9c of the 2c of\n                    <persName>Job</persName><lb/> was correctly rendered “curse God and die” after\n                examining<lb/> the Hebrew text I told him my impression was that<lb/> it should be\n                “Bless God and die” how then he asked<lb/> are we to account for the words in the\n                English Bible<lb/> I replied by the seventy translators regulating the points<lb/>\n                which have caused them to <add>?</add> gross <add>?</add> upon<lb/> many texts. That\n                without the several points we could<lb/> not understand the true meaning of\n                scripture, and<lb/> that by means of the amounts we are made to<lb/> understand the\n                subject matter, I maintain<add>?</add> my position<lb/> by the following examples.\n                The words in <persName>Job</persName> are<lb/>\n                <add>Hebrew</add> we read in 1<hi rend=\"sup\">st</hi> Gens 22<add>?</add> “and God\n                blessed”<lb/> using the letters and points <add>Hebrew</add> and in the 145 psalm\n                    <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> “bless the Lord” and in other places <add>Hebrew</add>\n                numbers 22<add>?</add>\n                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> the letters &amp; points the same that is used in\n                    <persName>Job</persName> 2c. 9c. the word<lb/> to curse in the 22c. 6 of numbers\n                is <add>Hebrew</add> and in <add>?</add>.28c<lb/> 16 to 19<add>?</add> to curse is\n                    <add>Hebrew</add> and the last word in the last verse<lb/> of the last chapter\n                of <add>?</add> to curse is <add>Hebrew</add> those were<lb/> all the authorities I\n                could find applicable to the subject<lb/> having no one in this congregation in\n                whose knowledge<lb/> I can confide. I without hesitation apply to you at<lb/> your\n                leisure forward me with your opinion discarding<lb/> all speculation as to the\n                motives of <persName>Jobs</persName> wife—wishing<lb/> you all happiness, I remain\n                your friend</p>\n            <p>Jacob Mordecai</p>\n            <p>ask <persName>Mrs Hart</persName> if she succeeded<lb/> in getting <add>?</add>\n                work</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p36q1t355/canvas/p1"
                }
